description._content: Rather like the 1963 Aston Martin DB5 I took an instant shine to the Hot Wheels Lotus Esprit S1 as I wasn't expecting a basic Mainline British sports car to look quite so accurate and well cast. Being an S1 means a totally pure wedge shaped bodywork completely free from later updates which softened the lines and added extra bodykit, just a wonderful slice of 70's wedginess! I think this casting was originally designed with a nod to the one used in the James Bond film The Spy Who Loved Me and so it was no surprise when it ended up in the 2015 James Bond series which mercifully U.K. collectors were able to find in various retailers. Its white colour is probably its finest yet with a completely uncluttered design with some really nice detailing especially at the rear. Bought from ASDA back in June 2016 and so i'm assuming it was when they were selling this range off, they may have many faults when it comes to diecast retailing but at least they don't let special edition HW models clog up the pegs any longer than they need to! Mint and boxed.

A 1986 Ford Capri with series x bodykit, photographed at the Capri Club International's 2015 National awards show, held at Badger's Hill in Worcestershire.
It's registered as a 3 litre, although this wouldn't have been the original engine size.

The Espirit was a mid engine sports car built by Lotus from 1976-2004, it replaced the Europa.
The 1976-78 Series 1, like most Lotus cars had a fibreglass body on a steel chassis, unique to the Series 1 was a shovel-style front air dam, Fiat X1/9 tail lights. Engine; 160hp 1973cc 4 cyl (Lotus 907)
The 1978-80 Series 2 got air duct behind the rear quarter window, tail lights from the Rover SD1, integrated front spoiler and new Lotus Speedline alloy wheels. 
149 black and gold JPS Specials were made in 1979. 
In 1980 engine size was increased to 2174cc (Lotus 912)
Also in 1980, the blue and red 211hp Essex Turbo (Lotus 910)
The 1981-87 Series 3 got more substantial bumpers, and a body kit, available with or without turbo. In 1986 the Espirit HC (High Compression) got 172hp and the Turbo Espirit HC got 215hp
The 1987-93 inbetween model was the X180, a less angular, more rounded car. 1989 saw the SE (Special Edition) with 264hp and bodykit
The 1993-2004 Series 4 got a smaller rear spoiler, revised bumpers, side skirts and valence panels. 1994 saw the S4S with new rear wing and 300hp and in 1996 the GT3, The last of the 4 cyl cars and the Espirit V8  (Type 918 500hp 214 cu in twin turbo V8)

description._content: Ikaho Toy, Doll and Car Museum May 2017

An Yunque GHK7071 photographed in Chengdu, Sichuan province, China.

A very interesting car today : the China-made 2nd gen Subaru Rex.

In late 1980's, the Guizhou Aircraft Company decided to develop its activities to automobile industry.
They created a JV with Subaru to produce in Anshun city in Guizhou province, in south China.

The first car produced was the GHK7060 which was a simple 2nd gen Rex.

In 1998, Yunque launched an upgrade version called "GHK7071" with several bodykits.

The company produced also the Subaru Rex and maybe an old gen Toyota Starlet.
The company was closed in 2003 and one year later Youngman purchased it to get the Yunque's license car production

I spotted this GHK7071 close to the huge used car market in south Chengdu.

Sadly, this Yunque is abandoned and probably will be scrapped.

It used the 4 cyl. Subaru 0.7 40hp.

Hopefully, I saw other, in much better shape.

Fiat Seicento (1997-2010)1100cc S4 Productiion 1,252,734 (UK sales 46,419) Registration Number W 10 TSN FIAT SET www.flickr.com/photos/45676495@N05/sets/72157623665060711... The Fiat Seicento (Type 187), as Fiats new city car, replacing the Cinquecento. With a design similar too, the Seicento, retaining the same engine, chassis and genral dimmensions though a little longer (9cm). and like its predecessor the Seicento was built in Fiat's factory in Tychy, Poland, At launch, the Seicento was available with three trim levels; a basic 'S' with black bumpers and spartan equipment and initially the 899 cc 39 PS FIAT 100 series engine, an SX model with improved trim and the S with colour coded bumpers electric windows, central locking and a sunroof, which was also available as a 'Citymatic' with a clutchless manual gearchange, and a 'Sporting' with the larger FIAT FIRE series 1,108 cc 55 PS engine In 1999, the FIRE engine was used in the special 'Suite' version, which came with air conditioning. In October 2000, after the update, all cars were given clear indicator lenses, with the Sporting model getting a restyled bodykit. In 2004, the model was withdrawn from the United Kingdom market] and production of RHD models ceased, following the arrival of the new and more practical Panda. The LHD model was facelifted, gaining a new design for the wheel rims and the introduction of the new Fiat logo to the rear.; This car has clearly been customised losing its logos and badges, so it is difficult to pin point the exact model, i concur with one of my Italian motoring contacts that it is probably a Mk,I 1998-00. Brooklands Italia Day 2015

The Romeo Ferraris Cinquone S is to a Fiat 500 Abarth as an Alpina or RUF is to a BMW or Porsche – externally similar, but legally a fully homologated road car separate from the vehicle that spawned it.
For more than 50 years, Romeo Ferraris has been tuning road cars, competing in various motorsport series around the world and – just because it’s cool – racing offshore powerboats. The eponymous Signor Ferraris founded his company in 1959 as a humble engine-builder. He quickly diversified into tuning and racing, forming close relationships with Fiat and BMW.
Romeo’s son Mario has since taken over the reins of the family business. Now based in Opera, near Milan, the company continues to race and tune road cars. With the Cinquone S, Romeo Ferraris is now a car manufacturer in its own right.
The Cinquone is available in three states of tune: a 158bhp entry-level version, a 207bhp S (driven here) and a range-topping Corsa model, which puts out a decidedly punchy 245bhp. With a kerb weight of 1030kg, the S has a power to weight ratio of 204bhp/ton.
All versions are remapped with Ferraris’ own software, while the more potent models also get a bigger turbo, an upgraded fuel injection system and a more freely flowing exhaust.
The latter two are capable of out-sprinting Fiat’s own Abarth 695 Biposto – 0-62mph takes a claimed 5.7sec in the S, and top speed is a quoted 144mph.
Taking an Abarth 500 as the starting point, Romeo Ferraris makes extensive modifications throughout, applies a new chassis number and reissues registration documents.
The homologation process is an expensive and arduous one made necessary by Italy’s draconian legislation that prohibits the modification of components away from OEM specification. In simple terms, Romeo Ferraris couldn’t legally sell tuning components in its homeland for road use, so it instead built a modified Abarth 500 to its own specification and homologated the thing.
It looks impossibly wide and pugnacious on the road, like an irritated bull terrier. It’s certainly the most aggressive 500-based road car we’ve ever come across; its gender realignment has been more comprehensive than Dame Edna Everage’s. The bespoke bodykit adds 26.6cm to the car’s overall width, with the arches filled by 18-inch wheels on a wider offset. The Cinquone is certainly not all skirt and no balls, though – a great deal of work has gone into the drivetrain and chassis as well. The suspension has been uprated with Bilstein dampers – developed specifically for the Cinquone – and Eibach springs, while the brakes are by Brembo.
With 207bhp from a 1.4-litre engine there is, naturally enough, a degree of lag in the lower reaches, but it’s not as marked as one might expect. From 2000rpm there’s a useable dose of torque, but from a little over 3000rpm the turbo really starts boosting and the car pulls very hard indeed.
Fiat’s own ludicrously expensive but hugely fun Abarth 695 Biposto is probably closest in spirit. Tick all the option boxes and the price approaches £50,000, but the open-gate dog-ring gearbox, polycarbonate windows, a data logger and other race-inspired components add immeasurable levels of theatre to the driving experience.
The company is now selling the Cinquone internationally and has a distributor in the UK – and you’ll pay about 60,722 euros (£44,700, as of March 2015) for the privilege.

The Lister Jaguar, designed by Brian Lister became a force in sportscar racing from 1957, and in more recent years the Lister name re-emerged in Sportscar and Endurance racing with the Lister Storm. From the early 1980's following agreements, firstly with BLE Automotive and then WP Automotive, saw converted XJ-S models marketed as Lister-Jaguars. This car has the full Lister bodykit and is powered by a tuned version of the Jaguar V12 HE (High Efficiency) engine.
